RedFlags: Piotroski F-Score (Overall Financial Strength) is a number between 0 - 9 which is used to assess the strength of a company's financial position. F-Score in the range of 8-9 is considered to be a High Performer, a range of 3-7 a Moderate Performer & 0-2 is considered a Weak Performer.

Overall Financial Strength Test is the sum of Profitability Strength, Leverage & Liquidity Strength, and Operating Efficiency. Profitability Strength is a number between 0 to 4; Leverage & Liquidity Strength is a number between 0 to 3; and Operating Efficiency is a number between 0 to 2.

The Beneish model is a statistical model that uses financial ratios to check if it is likely (high probability) that the reported earnings of the company have been manipulated. If M-Score is less than -2.22 , the company is unlikely to be a manipulator and if the M-Score is greater than -2.22, then the company is likely to be a manipulator.

The Altman Z Score is used to predict the chance of a business organization to move into bankruptcy.If the value is > 2.99, then there is no Financial distress, if the value is  <= 2.00 and >= 1.23 then it is said to have Moderate Financial distress, and if the value is < 1.23 then it is said to have Higher Financial distress.
Montier's C-Score is used to determine whether a company is cooking the books.If a company scores 0 there is no evidence of earnings manipulation whilst 6 suggests there is lots of evidence.
